{{Orphan|date=May 2015}}

'''Servicewüste''' ({{IPA-de|ˈsœɐ̯vɪsˌvyːstə}}, ''service desert'') is a [[management]] [[buzzword]] coined in [[Der Spiegel]] by [[economics]] professor [[Hermann Simon]] in 1995, referring to "the total lack of acceptable services".<ref>[http://www.duden.de/suchen/dudenonline/servicew%C3%BCste Duden Online: Servicewüste]</ref>  It is used to describe a country, region or area where the [[service sector]] generally or [[customer service]] specifically is weak or completely undeveloped.<ref>[https://www.welt.de/print-welt/article663420/Das-Kreuz-mit-dem-Service.html Welt Online, 30 October 1995, ''Das Kreuz mit dem Service''.]</ref> The term has correspondingly [[derogatory|negative connotations]].

It is often used for [[Germany]], where it is perceived that many organizations do not offer any other services after the purchase of a product and do not consider customers' needs.  Generally repairs and maintenance will be done only after paying additional fees.  An example given by Simon is that in contrast to those in the [[United States]], German [[supermarket]] checkouts did not have an employee dedicated to sacking groceries.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9248874.html ''Servicewüste Deutschland'', in Spiegel Nr. 51/1995 S. 82]</ref>

== Bibliography ==
